The paper deals with the problem of polygonization of a planar point set, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a sequence of atomic moves called "stretches" and "twangs" to connect polygonizations, which involves manipulating the topology of the polygonal wraps of the point set. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also discusses the potential use of these moves for generating random polygons, which could be relevant to cs.GR (Graphics) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
